The IBM innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone was looking for the word that most accurately reflects IBM&#39;s strategy, the closest would probably be &quot;longevity.&quot;
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, a company that is perceived as very contemporary, and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The basis of this longevity was laid by the company&#39;s first boss, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the motto that many of the world&#39;s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto &quot;Think!&quot; it thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine, which began publishing in IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the basis of Watson&#39;s carefully built corporate culture.
&quot;For us at IBM, long - term thinking means a continuous move towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values without being afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope to be able to achieve even more in the second hundred, &quot;said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company&#39;s current director, on the anniversary.
Sophisticated system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the care of his employees similarly to Baťa&#39;s entrepreneur in the Czech Republic - IBM people were one of the first American employees to have paid leave, employer insurance plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system for rewarding the best inventors and traders.
IBM has a long-standing relationship with the customer.
From the beginning, the company has been a genius in talent mining - as one of the world&#39;s first companies to eliminate any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisana to be headed by IBM next year - a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, and still holds the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called pits, online brainstorming, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder there are plenty of ideas - the company employs almost half a million people.
Institutions with a good reputation
A strong position in business is ensured by the company&#39;s strong internal and external image.
&quot;From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company,&quot; Rosh Moss Kanter, a professor at Harvard Business School and author of an IBM book, told the Economist.
&quot;IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology,&quot; added George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, the difference between entering the market and creating the market right away.
IBM - or &quot;Big Blue&quot;, as it is famously known for its logo in the United States - has grown into one of the world&#39;s largest companies in a hundred years.
It is probably the most versatile technology company - it develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include, for example, an ATM, a payment card, a financial swap, a bar code or a floppy disk.
IBM, with about $ 220 billion, became the second largest technology company by market capitalization this year (Apple is the first) when it overtook Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations have met the tastes of customers and times - for example, IBM has failed to bet on its own OS / 2 operating system, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers.
&quot;If your business is built on moving forward, you can&#39;t be emotionally attached to the past,&quot; notes Samuel J. Palmisano.
That&#39;s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms - and if they don&#39;t work, abandon them.
Unlike, for example, the competing Microsoft, which basically stands and falls on the Windows operating system.
Perspective technology
Services account for the largest share of IBM&#39;s revenues, with software and hardware accounting for about a fifth.
At the same time, in 1990 he was the strongest representative of hardware with more than a half share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $ 15 billion in low-yield assets, while investing $ 58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
It has continued to invest since 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time.
IBM is following the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to be intact with the current crisis.
The share price of IBM has risen by a rocket of 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, the company&#39;s net profit is constantly growing.
IBM&#39;s corporate motto is to change everything but its values.
It can therefore be expected that even if another crisis comes, this flexible giant will handle it.
IBM History: From the cheese slicer to space flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally with the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took over the name IBM only in 1924 - it was originally a brand used for the company&#39;s branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous &quot;punchers,&quot; ie hours that record the employee&#39;s arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the company&#39;s supervisory board.
Flint hired rival company firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM - an invincible corporate culture and identity are still built on Watson&#39;s ideas.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began manufacturing and selling all sorts of business machines - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson was in charge of the company, turnover doubled to nine million dollars and the company&#39;s extensive expansion to all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost forty years in his boss chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA control space flights - to Mercury, Saturn and, in 1969, the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System / 360 series.
The classic &quot;caregiver,&quot; which set the computer standard of the time, was called the IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer manufacturing business to Lenovo&#39;s Chinese company, bought PricewaterhouseCoopers&#39; consulting business, and began to focus fully on high value-added consulting and services.
The strategy that has paid off for IBM over the last three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, a &quot;smarter planet&quot;.
Its goal is the clever use of technology in hitherto unplanned areas, and the improvement of the situation, for example in transport or urban administration.
For business, IBM recently introduced the &quot;Smarter Commerce&quot; platform, which helps merchants manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
It established its branch in the then Czechoslovakia as early as 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM CR, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
