How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold the vast majority only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (ie also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually, even within socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or to have &quot;good acquaintances&quot; in the travel agency.
However, it was not won anyway.
The so-called the foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to &quot;politically unreliable people&quot; who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
By far the most common, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and chalets that the Czechs bought, and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989, holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we no longer realize today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to our currently most popular Croatia until 1989 until it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna and Germany in Austria.
For a long time, the Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to look there, at least for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czechs&#39; tours in the parks slept in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was bringing their own food, canned food, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy the Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with it our average salaries rose, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have been preparing to arrange tours on charter flights on a regular basis since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the historically first direct charter flight to exotics was sent from the Czech Republic to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters have been flying with Czech tourists to warm distant countries every year, and this winter it will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post - revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the USA canceled visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 thousand for one holiday abroad, including costs at the place of residence. CZK per person.
The general meeting is to find the chairman, but again there is a threat of a stalemate
For almost five months, Czech football has been without a chairman and there is a risk that Ivan Hašek&#39;s successor at the head of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FACR) will not be known even after another extraordinary general meeting, which will take place on Thursday in Nymburk.
There is still no agreement on which electoral rules will be followed.
Without it, there will be no vote on which of the three candidates will be elected.
Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík are interested in leading Czech football.
Hasek resigned in June and when he left he called on his colleagues to unite and find a strong personality who would lead football in the future.
But in the post-Hašek era, football slipped back to the quarrels between the two federal chambers, which cannot agree on a common candidate.
This became fully apparent on 16 September, when the new chairman was to be elected.
The delegates of the General Meeting gathered unnecessarily at the National House in Prague-Smíchov, as the meeting remained blocked and it was not just a matter of election.
There was no agreement on who has the right to vote at the meeting - whether only the statutory representatives or even the officials authorized by the power of attorney.
There has been a partial consensus on this single point since then, which was helped by the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law, according to which representation on the basis of a power of attorney is not possible.
But there are still disputes over the electoral order.
The executive committee, which is no longer dealing with anything else in its meetings, whether regular or extraordinary, has not brought the situation too clearly.
The view of choice has changed several times, but the neuralgic point is still the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the 3rd round to exclude the possibility of a heel?
&quot;The dispute is whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or find another model,&quot; said Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of the FACR, who represents professional football in the leadership of the association.
According to the model proposed by the statutes, in the third round, the candidate with the greater percentage support in the chamber for which he is running will win.
Moravia is reportedly willing to go for a concession to win a candidate who gets a higher sum of percentages of votes from both chambers.
And the Czech side enforces the condition that the winner must gain at least a two-thirds advantage in this percentage census.
&quot;But then the two previous rounds would lose its meaning, it would completely negate the two-chamber concept,&quot; he understands the objections of the Moravian party Svoboda, according to which it would be best not to bend and vote according to valid statutes.
Somewhat surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees with this, although it is estimated that the electoral rules determined by the statutes suit Pelt the most.
&quot;I want to be elected according to the statutes at most.&quot;
&quot;In order not to invent any surrogate nonsense as at the last general meeting,&quot; said the owner Viktorie Plzeň, who is running for the first time and in his statements he defined himself mainly against Pelt.
Pelta remains optimistic.
According to him, the new president will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will cooperate constructively together in the future.
&quot;All passions will be calmed by today&#39;s possible progress of the national team to the European Championships.&quot;
&quot;Football will be on a happy wave again, there will be a greater willingness to cooperate,&quot; says the Jablonec official, who has the greatest experience of managing football at both the professional and regional levels.
Rajchl is more reserved.
&quot;I hope for a deal, but unfortunately the situation is very divided.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s not among the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are efforts to purposefully adapt the regulations.&quot;
&quot;This may cause the general meeting to be blocked again.&quot;
&quot;But I hope common sense wins,&quot; Rajchl said.
There is not much time left for an agreement of all parties.
Some negotiations were supposed to take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows if the football general will be complete by the match.
The air special, in which Vice-Presidents Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl, among others, were to travel to Podgorica, did not leave Prague in the morning due to a technical failure, and an alternative option was sought to transport part of the executive committee to the site of the retaliation.
In the end, a ministerial meeting may be decisive, which may reportedly take place on Wednesday.
The Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, Josef Dobeš, would like to get the divided parties within the strongest sports association in the country to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state subsidies, the credibility of football and also the upcoming general meeting of ČSTV, which will address the new direction of Czech sport after Sazka&#39;s financial problems.
Paclík goes to fight for the chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
If the head of the football players of Pilsen, Tomáš Paclík, had seen a strong candidate before the extraordinary general meeting, who would have met all his ideas about the new chairman of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FACR), he would not even have signed up for the top position.
