Paclík claims that he would dare to lead the association.
He relies on his skills in managing private companies, and since last summer he has also been the head of Pilsen, which, with his support, celebrated its premier league triumph in May.
&quot;I have the strength to make a difference in the football environment to contribute to a certain cultivation of it.&quot;
&quot;In order to limit the influences of some interest groups, which, for example, tend to influence the disciplinary and appeals commission, which treats into disgusting situations,&quot; said Paclík, who does not hide his antipathy to, for example, the Spartan boss Daniel Křetínský.
He would also consider the strengthening of the FACR&#39;s relations with the Czech Olympic Committee to be one of its priorities, with the help of which it would lobby political leaders to get more money from the lottery tax into sports.
&quot;It&#39;s one of the key things the new president should do.&quot;
&quot;If gambling is taxed, as the political parties declare, I understand their argument, but they have to say, flatly, where the money will go,&quot; he said.
Paclík now does not take his connection with the Pilsen club as a burden, although he himself claims that the chairman of the FACR should be &quot;supra-party&quot;.
Pelta is again connected with Jablonec, Rajchl with Prague&#39;s Dukla.
&quot;It&#39;s not perfect.&quot;
&quot;But I don&#39;t even see the point of hypocritically transferring my shares to someone in the Pilsen club and returning there in a year and a half,&quot; Paclík said.
