Suddenly, he then takes responsibility for the strategy of the bank, which once again proved that it deserves the title &quot;Bank of the biggest scandals in Europe&quot;.
Because UBS is huge - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and it has been slipping from one scandal to another for years.
The proud Swiss bank does not seem to be spared anything.
It started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS enjoyed an excellent reputation.
The image of a secretive and solid, but also clever asset manager is combined with ambitious goals: She also wanted to mean something in investment banking.
On the one hand, UBS 2007, with $ 1.6 trillion, managed more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
On the other hand, as an investment bank, it has advanced into the league of the world&#39;s largest banks
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later long-time professor of banking in Zurich, said: &quot;At that time, I always referred UBS to my students as a model for a good bank.&quot;
&quot;From today&#39;s point of view, one asks: How could I be so wrong?&quot;
He was very wrong.
In 2007, it was clear for the first time that something had gone wrong at UBS.
Surprisingly, the head of the board of directors, Peter Wuffli, resigned in the middle of the year and was previously considered a highly intelligent and also brilliant banker.
A few months later, he wondered why he had left.
The bank&#39;s investment division wasted Subprime-papers and had to write off billions.
To keep this going, UBS announced a capital increase of really 13 billion francs.
Instead, she did find investors, but those she would have recently turned her nose over: An opaque Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so discreet that one didn&#39;t even know its name.
But that was only the first impact.
In April 2008, it developed worse.
The bank had to admit new billions in losses, and Marcel Ospel, the president of the board of directors, the second highest paid board of directors in Switzerland in 2006, resigned.
A disaster ensued in October 2008: UBS faced a collapse due to its misinvestment during the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
Nationalbank bought troubled securities from UBS for tens of billions, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs on mandatory convertible bonds, for which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland has been shaken - for noticing how dramatic it is for a small country to have such large banks on its territory.
After all, the balance sheet total of UBS 2007 was more than five times higher than the performance of the Swiss economy (see figure).
&quot;Once again, we could not save UBS,&quot; says banking expert Geiger.
The first catastrophe is followed by the second.
For several months now, UBS has capitulated in a tax dispute with America and has shown a willingness to release data from wealthy customers who, if possible with the help of banks, cut taxes.
In addition, it agreed to pay $ 780 million - as a refund of the illicit profits from these transactions, including a penalty surcharge.
In doing so, UBS admitted more or less openly that it helped reduce taxes.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for wealthy clients: a halo of discretion.
After this scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer what it used to be.
This was followed by the resignation of the head of the board of directors and the president of the board of directors.
And the exodus of customers&#39; money.
Thus, within a few months, the bank lost its credibility in both central business areas: in investment banking due to bad speculation and in asset management to help with tax cuts.
And just as it calmed down a bit, just as UBS was thought to have recovered, here comes this unfortunate business anabasis: A single dealer wasted 1.7 billion euros before the bank noticed something was wrong.
And it&#39;s clear: risk management in investment banking probably still doesn&#39;t work.
&quot;In the case of Adoboli, it has probably been found that risk control has changed too little,&quot; says Martin Janssen, an economist and Finanz professor of finance at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also sure: &quot;The problem with UBS is that it does not manage risk control.&quot;
At the same time, it was precisely the idea of caution that Swiss bankers set out with a long time ago to become the guardians of the world&#39;s great assets: no excessive risks, but security for money - the Alpine Republic also collapsed again.
The safes of Swiss banks have become a symbol for unshakable reliability, like Lindt and Sprüngli for high-quality chocolate.
UBS&#39;s headquarters in Zurich is still in line with the cliché of a good Swiss private bank - it&#39;s just a little bigger.
The location is already classic.
The bank is headquartered in Zurich&#39;s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are beautiful, the rental shops are among the tallest in Europe.
Jewelry stores like Tiffany&#39;s can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as Sprüngli patisseries.
Swiss banks have been based here for centuries: from Nationalbank to the Palast der Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Bär.
The UBS reception hall is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are lined with marble, in front of them are massive leather armchairs, next to the bank&#39;s logo, a large signpost to the &quot;safe&quot;.
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
However, the Swiss bank&#39;s idea was suppressed or betrayed by both Swiss big banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds out.
He would rather not read his name in the newspapers, in the end he, like all Swiss bankers, also closes with both big banks.
UBS has probably grown too much, he finds out - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss probably have nothing more to say about it.
&quot;And if they did, they had long ago adapted to Anglo-Saxon manners.&quot;
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, bringing it high profits at first and then disaster: No European financial institute lost as much money in the jungles around Subprime as Schweizer Großbank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster was obvious.
&quot;On that Wednesday, the governing coalition of a small seven-million-strong country decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of its nation,&quot; writes author Lukas Hässig in his book &quot;Der UBS-Crash&quot;.
As many as 68 billion francs, or about 45 billion euros, have been approved by politicians to save the big bank from bankruptcy.
How could this have happened?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, you see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three Swiss large banks merged into a large group.
A bank was formed that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and it continued to grow.
At the same time, it helped that the two different banking predecessors of UBS complemented each other: One rich but sleepy bank in Zurich with a focus on asset management and a poorer but more internationally involved one.
Suddenly, internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of money with which to spin big roulette.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, head of the UBS Group from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then chairman of the board.
&quot;I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were the team of the future,&quot; says banking expert Hans Geiger.
&quot;Wuffli, the highly intelligent, humble one who knows a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the stomach-driven man who has worked his way up from banking science.&quot;
But Ospel allegedly relied on Wuffli in the end.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: &quot;He probably thought his models were a reality,&quot; says Geiger.
&quot;That&#39;s a tragic case.&quot;
Tragic, perhaps.
It is clear: Pride preceded the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which Wuffli, the group&#39;s chief, repeated the same motto over and over again: knocking Goldman Sachs down from the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She featured &quot;League Tables,&quot; a queue that documents the success of the banks of the time.
In it, UBS tried to place it at the very top.
She had already taken a few steps.
In the foreign exchange and stocks trade, she participated in the game at the very top.
However, the business advisers who were commissioned point to one weakness: In international interest rate trading, in the words of &quot;Fixed Income&quot; bankers, there is probably a big gap behind the largest banks.
UBS probably has gaps in US mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS decided on an adventure that almost cost her to exist.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and its hedging fund have invested in US Subprime investments.
It developed into a massive machine that repackaged securities into American mortgages and passed them on - but it also kept the risks itself.
Also when other banks had long been looking for a way out.
&quot;Back in the summer of 2007, when the real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,&quot; says banking expert Geiger.
How great is the euphoria, so is the deep fall.
One manager after another had to leave when attempts to clean up were more difficult than previously thought.
The positions at UBS have become a catapult seat and they are still rocking.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost unmanageable job.
He must find a strategy for the bank, which all nearby business models have disappeared.
Banking expert Geiger already has an idea: Ending investment banking, concentrating on asset management, returning to Swiss roots.
The bank does not want to go that far yet.
But investment banking is set to decline sharply, so much is now clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Swiss Italian was actually seen only as a temporary solution, when the bank surprisingly broke up with its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has asserted himself: He has to run UBS business for a long time, the Zurich bank said on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to normal in the mid-1990s.
3500 seats cut.
But that will not be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does he want to make money?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking.
But so far he is only saying publicly that he will first find an apartment in Zurich with his mistress.
Next year.
