Intelligent crows are spreading in cities
In many places, field ravens are considered &quot;problem birds&quot;: However, these highly intelligent animals can no longer be expelled from cities, experts say.
Some like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the city&#39;s image for centuries, yet in some villages, the complaints of residents about dirt and noise caused by animals are accumulating.
At the same time, there is no means in sight against &quot;problem birds&quot;.
Field ravens can probably no longer be expelled from the cities, experts said at the first symposium about crows in Leer in East Frisia.
There, experts from all over the federal territory consulted on possible solutions.
They are looking for alternatives in cities
At the same time, conservationists also derived the problems of cities from the exodus of specially protected field ravens: The use of chemistry in agriculture is probably destroying traditional areas for life.
The chasing, growing development and felling of typical trees to nest birds make life difficult.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 nesting pairs are in Soest, Westphalia, in the northwest, among others, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and Leer, among others.
There, a 2005 controversial project of mass killing crows in a rural district provoked negative headlines.
Critics have called trapping animals in bird traps and killing sticks particularly brutal.
&quot;Normal expulsion, scare, does not bring anything,&quot; found out urban planner and landscaper Werner Klöver from Leer.
Removing nests by spraying water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
&quot;The animals retreat, the large colonies split and divide into other places.&quot;
Scare is conceivable only as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
&quot;We have to live with them, we won&#39;t get them away.&quot;
Without the surrounding area, the problem of cities cannot be solved, was the opinion of Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable to combine animals from sensitive residential areas and attract them to settle elsewhere.
&quot;Information board instead of chainsaws&quot;, on the other hand, was promoted by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens because of a completely different treatment of animals: &quot;One piece of face in the face can best end with confidence.&quot;
Ms. Jürgens co-founded the Ascherberg Educational Crow Trail in Schleswig-Holstein, on which information boards provide instruction on the life of a highly intelligent field raven.
The project is said to have been accepted by tourists in the meantime.
Ms. Jürgens also had her own opinion of the criticism of the noise caused by the birds: &quot;This is every volume of communication, they have a lot to say.&quot;
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: Field ravens do not only use aids to achieve a treat, but even make their own tool.
Researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested the behavior on four ravens of the birds&#39; intelligence.
