Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund&#39;s emotionally powerful new book, Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with such a long list of emerging characters that it makes you dizzy.
One piece of advice on how to behave at the moment: Carefully tear out this page and bookmark it.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund&#39;s novel, and this list will serve as a navigation - like a kind of beacon - in moments when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new Deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as an &quot;antihistorical work&quot;.
It contains several well-known names, important treaties and famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather a &quot;book about what it was like&quot;. It deals mainly with &quot;feelings, impressions, experiences and moods&quot;.
&quot;Beauty and Grief&quot; combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go insane, or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of destinies, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund&#39;s book differs from classic historical novels.
It modifies the idea that the First World War was just about the terrible trench fighting on the Western Front.
&quot;Beauty and grief&quot; skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
In this book, soldiers deal with the problem of bee nests falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shade of pyramids, or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
It is a very touching reading almost from the beginning.
The war consumes people&#39;s lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts in the distance and you are a woman at home with your children, will you run away or stay?
Who is actually approaching?
Almost no one understands what&#39;s going on, not even why the whole war was started.
&quot;The vacuum created by the lack of facts,&quot; Mr. Englund noted, &quot;was filled with conjecture, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.&quot;
&quot;Beauty and Grief&quot; follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and engaging, but thanks to the incorporation of small moments and details, they are absolutely lively and believable.
Many of them deal with suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: &quot;Substitutes, substitutes everywhere.&quot;
&quot;Coffee substitute, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons.&quot;
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
He mentions &quot;meat made from pressed rice cooked in mutton (and supplemented with a false wood bone), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles&quot;.
It mentions that there were &quot;837 registered meat substitutes for sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes&quot;.
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds inner impulses to savagery and brutality, and then declares about the war: &quot;In the end, you will understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a good book and pretend that your mask it represents civilization, and that there is no barbarian inside that starchy self. &quot;
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone mourn.
&quot;When one finally comes to terms with sacrificing oneself, one would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience,&quot; he writes.
Instead, however, he feels like &quot;a convict he is secretly hanged.&quot;
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
&quot;The conflict has become more and more of an economic competition and a competitive struggle,&quot; writes Mr. Englund, &quot;a war between factories.&quot;
He captured what he calls &quot;a new kind of beast of the coming century: an eloquent and ideologically sworn mass murderer in a tailor-made dress who carries out his bloodshed without getting up from the table.&quot;
People behave completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes in order to avoid service at the front.
&quot;The most grotesque example of this behavior was the trade in gonococcal pus, which soldiers bought and rubbed their genitals in the hope that they would end up in hospital,&quot; he writes.
&quot;The most desperate people rubbed it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives.&quot;
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund&#39;s prose is brisk but not flashy, which is a great match for his human subject.
In dozens of small outputs, he captures the way in which the war &quot;unleashed completely unmanageable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.&quot;
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books on World War I mostly worked with hints rather than a comprehensive narrative, such as &quot;World War I and Modern Memories&quot; by Paul Fussell or novels like &quot;Peace on the Western Front&quot; by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr Englund prefers an unconventional approach.
His book has the most overwhelming ending, unparalleled in popular science literature.
However, I will not reveal it to you.
However, you will feel as if the author suddenly jumped out of the book, snatched the page from the list of heroes from your hand and set it on fire.
After a previous mistake, this time for a minute a precisely planned raid
