Other teams of police officers were seen gathering at the edge of the park to break into it if any arrests were needed.
Reporters were forced to leave the park.
Police chief spokesman Paul J. Browne said it was for their safety.
However, many journalists believe that the police wanted to prevent them from seeing their troops in action, and that some police officers treated them rudely.
Mr. Browne claimed that television cars on Church Street running along the western boundary of the park could shoot without any problems.
Police advanced westward, tangled in a thick tangle of protesters&#39; personal belongings, including luggage and plastic bags full of clothes. Teams from the hygiene department set out after them, immediately raking in everything that was left in the park.
Some protesters who refused to move were dragged out of the park. Documentary images appeared on the Internet shortly afterwards.
The most ardent group of protesters took refuge near the kitchen in their camp, which lay near the center of the park.
Some created a roadblock and police initiated their methodological arrests.
About ten people in the center of the camp were strapped together.
And two people were tied to a tree, Mr. Kelly said.
Emergency service members were called to cut the locks.
There were no arrests in the park until 3:30 in the morning, Mr. Kelly said.
The whole operation was completed about 75 minutes later, the police said.
Mr Browne said about 142 people had been detained in the park.
Most of the arrests were for &quot;organizing riots and resisting arrests,&quot; he explained.
The highest ranking police officer at the scene was Joseph J. Esposito, commander of the police department, the highest ranked uniformed officer on the department.
Phil T. Pulaski, the detective&#39;s commander in the department, also personally participated in the operation.
Mr. Kelly was present, but &quot;did not participate in the management of the operation,&quot; Mr. Browne said.
A second group of officers waited along the east side of Broadway, between Liberty Street and Cedar Street, in case she needed to be called.
Barricades were erected on Cortlandt Street, a block north of the park, and on Pine Street, a block south of the park.
From these places, the police then developed a protective belt even further from Zuccotti Park.
At one point, police officers, many of whom were equipped with shields, were seen pushing people even further beyond the border.
There were about 28 people on the northern border.
The wildest events of the night took place south of the park.
At around five in the morning, a protester south of Pine Street was spotted jumping on the hood of a police car and several others bleeding from the tires of a police van.
At one point, a piece of plywood flew out of the crowd.
At the end of the operation, one police officer and one protester were hospitalized.
The auxiliary union will sue the city for dismissal
Trade unions representing hundreds of school assistants who lost their jobs last month plan to sue the city on Wednesday. He claims that the redundancies were not necessary and, moreover, discriminated against because of the disproportionate impact on the schools attended by poor students.
Judicial proceedings are probably the last option left to trade unions in District Council 37 in their efforts to overturn redundancy decisions.
On October 7, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parental coordinators, and other employees who were among the city&#39;s lowest-paid employees lost their jobs. Their dismissals were described by union leaders as retaliation by the city for failing to give it access to a platoon-managed health care fund last spring, with which the city wanted to close a hole in the budget.
City officials categorically denied the allegations.
At a city council meeting last month, Education Secretary Dennis M. Walcott said the redundancies were part of a budget approved in June.
One of the board members immediately countered by saying that the budget did not specifically mention the dismissal of auxiliary staff.
District Council officials 37 announced that they had already completed the necessary documents and warned the Department of Education that they would sue him. They will call a press conference on Wednesday to formally file a lawsuit in Manhattan&#39;s Supreme State Court.
The defendants in the trial will be Mr. Walcott and the Department of Education, while the plaintiffs will be eight fired workers, all of whom are African Americans or Hispanics, as well as most other assistants who have lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city&#39;s legal department, said the city had not yet seen the lawsuit and would not comment on the allegations.
According to a complaint filed by the New York Times, unions focused on the number of redundancies in poor parts of the city in support of their allegations of unfair treatment. They are of the opinion that poor schools have lost more assistants because they have been denied sufficient funding for a long time.
They point out that while schools in Staten Island were not made redundant and only minimally in the Upper East Side, in Brooklyn, District 23 in Brownsville, 17 school assistants lost their jobs and in District 8 and 9 in the South Bronx, even 46 assistants were fired.
He points out that five out of eight assistants lost their jobs at Public School 36 in Harlem, even though it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says: &quot;This is not a neighborhood full of mobile parents who can raise funds to cover the budget deficit.&quot;
Public School 36&#39;s budget was reduced by 3.26 percent this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way bonus funds were calculated for each poor student enrolled.
Unions claim, among other things, that high school principals may have been confused by the way in which the document approving the dismissal of parental coordinators was written.
In the document, the word &quot;excess&quot; was used to describe the action, ie to cancel the position, although this word is much more often used to describe the transfer of a teacher from the school&#39;s payroll to a database of available staff whose salary is paid by the central authority.
&quot;Sixty-six parental coordinators have been fired,&quot; says the complaint, &quot;and not just moved to the database to the position of available staff.&quot;
The mission is over, Congress is ready to accept an agreement on the situation in Libya
Finally, Republicans and Democrats in Congress seem to agree on something about the uprising in Libya.
But before that could happen, the revolution had to succeed, the long-reigning dictator Muammar Gaddafi had to be captured and killed, and the participation of United States troops ended.
