Over the summer, lawmakers on both sides have been constantly arguing with each other and with the White House over a series of statements approving or rejecting the United States&#39; military role in NATO&#39;s mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain passed a resolution authorizing the limited use of US forces in Libya.
The proposal was rejected in the Chamber due to differing opinions of both political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that the proposal was rejected in the House, the chamber also rejected a measure that would stop the financing of US operations in Libya.
As a result, the US mission in Libya was literally in a legislative purge - Congress criticized President Obama&#39;s management of the mission, but his members were clearly not irritated enough to stop supporting him.
The hesitation of the congress was eventually preceded by other events.
The rebels conquered Tripoli in August, and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
Now the Senate may be ready to act.
In a statement, the Commission on International Relations &quot;congratulates the people of Libya on their immense courage and admirable tenacity in their efforts to liberate their people&quot; and &quot;commends the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their allies involved in the operation to protect the Libyan people&quot;. , for extraordinary bravery and professionalism. &quot;
The statement also &quot;confirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya.&quot;
Will the new proposal gain the full support of the Commission on International Relations, or will the legislators again be divided into two halves, as was the case when the June proposal was approved?
Senator Richard G. Lugar (Ind.), The Republican leader&#39;s main representative on the commission, opposed the latest version.
Lugar&#39;s spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
This week, the House will vote on an amendment to the Constitution that would require a balanced budget, which should be the highest legislative priority for almost all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
This measure, promoted by Bob Goodlatt (Va.), Will be the first amendment to the Constitution on a budget or other topic to be voted on by the entire House or Senate.
For the time being, despite considerable efforts, the other legislators have not yet managed to push their proposals to the vote itself.
Goodlatt&#39;s proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the constitution that were presented in Congress and touched on a wide range of topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal submitted to the House and the Senate - and others are only minor variations of others.
In the House alone, there are at least 15 versions of the balanced budget amendment and another handful that would like to &quot;regulate federal spending.&quot;
While some of the proposals are identical, their proponents - especially budding Republicans who want to improve their reputation - can boast of &quot;authorship.&quot;
The decree on the regulation of the budget, which was approved in August, required the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate to vote on the amendment concerning the balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding statement in support of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss limiting the number of terms in which members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (NY) wants to increase the number of terms that can be held as president.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) Offered a number of amendments that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
An amendment banning same-sex marriage and an amendment banning the burning of the national flag remain a permanent proposal.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be repealed if two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress appear to be very active in proposing various amendments, they do not deviate significantly from the average compared to previous years.
In the 111th Congress they offered 77 amendments, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales in comparison with the early 1990s, when, according to statistics from the Senate Library, members offered more than 150 additions every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than current politicians.
The last amendment added - the 27th Amendment - was ratified in 1992, but was in fact proposed by Congress in 1789.
