&quot;They were all introduced as orphans,&quot; the officer wrote in an e-mail.
I&#39;m sure the organizers meant well.
I know I do.
But what I saw was not respect. It was a pity.
Such completely opposite impressions only illustrate the difficult relationship between the military and the often measured, sometimes celebrating American public.
The army is gratelessly embraced by praise for its victims.
But this praise costs something, say the soldiers.
The public is increasingly acting as if the individual in uniform is sorry.
&quot;We are not victims at all,&quot; said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and will soon leave Afghanistan.
&quot;But it seems that the only way some can support us is to put us in the role of unhappy souls.&quot;
This topic is very sensitive for army commanders who do not want to look ungrateful or spoil relations with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger that troops once returning from Vietnam had to face was much worse.
As a result, most words of remorse are uttered in silence and privacy among war veterans.
When the two sons of retired Colonel Mark Cancian returned from combat operations where they served as members of the Marines, their father warned them that people outside the army would look at their service from two angles.
From the point of view of some, they will feel respect and amazement, because they defeated the enemy insurgents and visited exotic places.
But others will be wondering if &quot;an evil, violent veteran is hiding beneath the surface,&quot; said Cancian, who took part in the fighting in Iraq and took his place in the Washington government when he returned.
He claimed that when he was looking for a job, some people who interviewed him discreetly indicated whether he could withstand the stress of working in Washington so soon after returning from fighting.
&quot;When you talk about your ministry, you have to reckon with negative reactions,&quot; Cancian instructed his sons.
The military&#39;s concern stems in part from American indifference to wars.
Success on the battlefield seldom reaps recognition in a country that has little awareness of its own military and finds little benefit in the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
&quot;As a nation, we no longer value military heroism as it was common during World War II,&quot; said Lieutenant General David Barno, who commanded US troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, recognition from politicians and the public focuses mainly on the suffering of men in arms.
Soldiers are honored for the number of actions they suffered, the number of friends they lost, or the extent of their injuries.
