The team defending the Department of Defense is led by United States Attorney Neil MacBride, who, along with his colleagues, has filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents obtained by Newsweek analyze in detail the defense strategy - basically, the point is that current or former soldiers cannot sue the military for injuries they have suffered as members of the armed forces.
Under a 1950 Supreme Court order called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries sustained by soldiers in active service.
&quot;The alleged injuries concern the military service of the plaintiffs,&quot; the document said.
The Ministry of Defense declined to comment on the matter.
But things have changed since the 1950s.
