Following this summer&#39;s tragedy, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
&quot;We realized that getting them isn&#39;t really that hard,&quot; said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent British research team report on European digital populism.
The supply of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, it was enough for researchers to simply use advertising on the site to determine the demographic group they were looking for with absolute precision - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett&#39;s team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, then turned their attention to them and sent them ads. However, instead of inviting them to a newly formed group or offering them some diet products, they encouraged them to complete a questionnaire asking them about their level of education, their relationship to violence and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without having to leave the office at all.
&quot;It&#39;s a whole new way of doing research,&quot; notes Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men, who are outraged by the growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, &quot;those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more sensible, democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.&quot;
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hiding status updates, wall posts and &quot;Like&quot; buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides, on average, three different data a day, making this social network literally an &quot;information supernova&quot; behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic theses with the word Facebook in the title has increased to almost 800% compared to five years ago.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
&quot;It used to be that when you wanted to conduct a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.&quot;
&quot;You&#39;d have to get to the side, but they&#39;d never let you go,&quot; says Bartlett.
&quot;Facebook is breaking down all this - you&#39;re just going straight to them.&quot;
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken outcomes on Facebook were much more vulnerable to alcoholism than students who were silent on the subject.
Moren suggests that student peers monitor the site and offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
&quot;The problem can&#39;t be solved if you can&#39;t diagnose it,&quot; Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moren and director of the Center for Children&#39;s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children&#39;s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
&quot;We&#39;ve found a way to identify at-risk children we wouldn&#39;t otherwise have a chance to discover.&quot;
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The information team of the website compiled statistics concerning the connection between the relationship statuses and the day of St. Valentine&#39;s Day, turnout in 2010 and the nation&#39;s satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - proponents of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available to others for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don&#39;t even know about?
Researchers have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
&quot;I don&#39;t think most users even thought that researchers could look at their profiles,&quot; said Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he carried out using his students&#39; public Facebook walls.
&quot;As for them, they took it that the information was just between them and their friends.&quot;
Subsequently, the question of methodology is also considered.
Even with off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the wall are true.
&quot;What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,&quot; Selwyn explains.
That&#39;s why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, thinks that the pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
&quot;When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it&#39;s something you can&#39;t replace,&quot; he says.
&quot;Social research should be about society and social activities - and a hell of a lot of social activities are still taking place off-line.&quot;
