How to recognize a lie
A cursory glance at recent headlines suggests how serious and ubiquitous lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy accusing him of sexually harassing several women - both sides claiming the other is lying.
Penn State University administrators have been accused of perjury when they tried to hide records that a retired football coach had sexually assaulted a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling US President Barrack Obama with a microphone open that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie was able to destroy entire careers and obscure the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself when he published information that was immediately refuted by unquestionable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing funds from his campaign to try to conceal his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that swept around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating at school and university are all over the place.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many scams do we encounter?
Studies show that you lie between 10 and 200 cases in a single day.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of the first meeting in their lives.
Determining lies, or &quot;recognizing lies&quot;, is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or work reasons.
However, it is not a board game similar to, say, Sharada, where one shouts, &quot;I have you.&quot; Deception recognition is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars look into your eyes.
It&#39;s not like they stutter, stutter, blush or fidget.
However, do not deduce from the fact that it is somehow difficult to observe and reveal liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are formed and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a large and evolving lie detection industry, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can help you a lot in today&#39;s complex world - especially if your work responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them relax in vigilance, direct their emotions and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more &quot;self-centered&quot; lies, while women tell more lies &quot;focused on others&quot; - mostly to protect someone&#39;s feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people. (But the lies they tell are usually &quot;outrageous&quot;).
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone is lying?
First, observe the subject&#39;s normal behavior.
This is called &quot;initial observation&quot;.
Thanks to him, he will have later findings to compare with.
Notice the posture of the subject, his laughter, the work with the voice.
You should know if someone is constantly tapping their feet so that you don&#39;t unjustifiably accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But take it only as a warning signal, not as evidence of a lie.
People telling lies can stop moving their upper body as they try to remember their fictional story, they can point their toes to the door, lean to the exit, significantly change their posture, or show &quot;relief after the conversation&quot; - exaggerated relief and change positions when confession is difficult behind them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like after the interview.
Also perceive the language of the subject.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once argued and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which launched a nationwide search for her body.
Deceiving individuals may also express themselves in a measured manner: &quot;I had no sexual relationship with that lady ... Miss Lewinsky&quot; or they repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are only very slight.
Someone can use a lot of &quot;mitigating language&quot; when answering a difficult question: &quot;Well ... to tell the truth ... from what I know ... to the best of my knowledge.&quot;
We do not know much about such an answer and it is often another warning signal.
There is no spell that can expose every lie, but it is possible to acquire skills that can be used to track down a lie.
With these skills, a person will have a better chance of not flying into a liar and a fraudster in his personal and professional life.
