A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday
Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government facing a crisis that is holding the country above the abyss of economic disaster.
Tomorrow&#39;s Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that is holding the country above the abyss of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone in danger.
The Presidential Palace has issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to introduce a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
&quot;I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country&#39;s ability to overcome this difficult phase,&quot; the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that obstacles had been overcome.
&quot;The framework is now well marked,&quot; he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to fight the political and financial crisis, which has brought debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders. Only in this way will it be possible to restore Italy&#39;s undermined credibility.
There is a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry. Due to market instability, interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a ten-year maturity exceeded 7 percent, a level where Greece and Ireland had to ask for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, chairwoman of the Italian employers&#39; organization Confindustria, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: &quot;We said we would be very supportive of this government.&quot;
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this burning situation.
Monti&#39;s hopes for success have greatly increased thanks to the support of PDL Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
&quot;We believe that Professor Monti&#39;s efforts are destined for good results,&quot; Angelina Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy&#39;s largest party, is significant because, to date, many of its members have opposed the government with a technocratic majority formed by Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined in the pressure to warn that Monti&#39;s failure could spell disaster.
Monti opened talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women&#39;s organizations.
The round of negotiations will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed President Napolitano on Sunday, who allowed a very rapid move in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline from the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, interest rates on Italian bonds returned to a critical level, responding to uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister would succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the scope of the eurozone&#39;s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next elections, which are scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will give him time only to carry out reforms and then call early elections. .
Monti said he would like to incorporate policies into his cabinet, but the big parties insist that the government must be made up of experts only to get Italy out of the difficulties the country has gotten due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual mistrust and disagreement between the parties complicate the attempt to integrate political figures into the government.
