The quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate twenty years of existence
&quot;Traveling to Costa Rica is a dream come true&quot;
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best gigs at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures them that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
That&#39;s what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is touring the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
This day will perform at 7:30 pm at the National Stadium, along with the angelic band The X and national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an example from an interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the La Nación website on the Internet.
This is a dream come true for your Costa Rican fans. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The trip to Costa Rica is also our dream come true.
This is hardly the second time in South and Central America and the experience so far has been great.
I&#39;ve only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It is a beautiful country and I believe that we will be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask because they literally adore the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparations very intensely.
What do you say to your most rock fans?
Thank you for standing with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we&#39;ve done in the last 21 years have been in a few weeks.
We put on some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get in shape for the concert in Costa Rica.
In fact, we are really looking forward to that concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. Costa Rica is the best country in the world for both activities.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfers and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
Looking at your tour, you&#39;ve prepared a great show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we&#39;ve never played here, we have no restrictions on what we can&#39;t do.
We will try to present the best possible show with various songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think it&#39;s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it&#39;s hard to choose what songs we&#39;re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven&#39;t played in a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised, because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that&#39;s why I think it&#39;s more interesting for people as well.
With this tour you are celebrating 20 years of artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you&#39;ve accomplished?
Yes, for sure.
First of all, I don&#39;t think any of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and we are impressed that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we like to make music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always longed for.
We couldn&#39;t have done better.
What did it mean for you to have been an important part of the origins of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the greats themselves are represented.
People from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn&#39;t happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of it and we are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate to be all our friends, and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to that we managed to open musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we respect each other&#39;s music and I don&#39;t think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word glory has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it gradually became easier to find balance.
We try not to tour too much, because it&#39;s very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not be carried away by being a famous rock star. Neither of us ever really cared about this.
How do you remember the next project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs and in the beginning it was something spectacular.
We existed as a band for three years and never released an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, we are still friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in a band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy was incredible, laughing at him. It has always been a joy to work with him, to laugh, to talk about music or football and much more.
He was an incredible person and we miss him so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose them as a frontman?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions, and we liked this group the most. That&#39;s why we&#39;re curious what Las Robertas has to offer live and they have to be a lot of fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That&#39;s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don&#39;t know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
A lot of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski are the first to attack me ...
There are so many that I could talk all night about bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam keep grunge, even though it&#39;s no longer in vogue?
I think we&#39;ve all always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When grunge is said, I imagine the groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else that were formed at the same time. And if the music is still valid today, it&#39;s great, because it&#39;s music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney play better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music was slightly gloomy and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
This is interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and the songs are deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs are just what they mean to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
