Park or mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of announcing a procedure that brings with it more than a controversy over fees
The city tender for 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park in metropolitan Barcelona.
What&#39;s more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York&#39;s Central Park.
After the demise of CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that does not orient itself on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boar instead of the Yogi bear.
Such was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
Of course, the gate favors the idea of the park.
Either this or someone is trying to place the gate on the field.
So the only question is: Collserola, a park or a mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and on the basis of a reflection on the city, this question becomes a central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It is already a topic as blunt as when two members of this old caste chosen to meet in an elevator shake hands.
And it was this act that provoked one of the rare coincidences between what the three Barcelona architects and the prominent university professors think.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the competition is justified.
According to Roldán, after the Gulf Party question began, &quot;the&quot; mountain side &quot;also needs to be discussed, so Ildefons Cerd&#39;s speech on green apples was not completed.
&quot;We have to start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex, &quot;said the architect, for whom the name&quot; gate to Collserola &quot;carries a&quot; lexicological trap &quot;: we must not imagine them&quot; as entrances to the park, but rather as the delimitation of zones where it is possible to operate. &quot;
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, describes the proposal as an &quot;intellectual challenge&quot; offering &quot;some danger&quot;.
The danger of the &quot;uncertainty posed by the public space project today&quot; after the experience of the 1980s, which had &quot;its swan singing&quot; in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very delimitation of the boundaries where it should be built.
&quot;Defining something means taking another step,&quot; that is, basically taking it a step further.
&quot;New urban and planning tools need to be kept in mind, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster.&quot;
If we focus on the question in more detail, Modol believes that the valley slope of Collserola can be &quot;considered a park&quot;, but the Barcelona part cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there was already work done by the Patronate de Collserola, which &quot;must not end up in the dump&quot;, although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers its board to intervene in the project from the &quot;first moment&quot;.
