The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched research into the gene that causes obesity
The Health Insurance Institute is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for childhood and adolescent obesity. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene that causes obesity in children and young people. Research entitled &quot;Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents&quot; will provide results on overweight.
In a report, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit at the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of postgraduate specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Research and Advanced Studies Center (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, whether or not authorized, may also be involved in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where tests will be performed on minors every room from 8 am.
He emphasized that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexican State) and, since 8 October, has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (Eastern Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity, and to track down risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is being celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with parental consent and supervision, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and a family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants take anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), measure blood pressure, determine glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol, insulin levels and examine genes (trying to identify the genes involved in the formation childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health careers&#39; concerns about the alarming increase in children&#39;s weight.
&#39;Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had an 77% increase in obesity and a 47% increase in girls. There has also been a dramatic increase in overweight, said an IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the country&#39;s population differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American-American genetic equipment, 30% European, and 5% African. This is reflected in the genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants was that they received an overall assessment of the children &#39;s condition, to see if they were known to be overweight or obese.
He stated that even the presence of dark wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar conditions.
The information is still confidential, doctors pass it on to parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make in order for their children to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle involving a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day and using vehicles instead of walking short distances.
Being overweight is also caused by a high caloric intake, i.e. higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) high in fat and protein and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in UNAM asphalt
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair almost 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de México metropolitan area, said Rafael Herrera Najera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who added that if construction and maintenance asphalt paving was adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or it would even be possible to remove them completely.
In his lecture, The Technological Cause of Pits, delivered at the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should produce a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt but greater mechanical resistance, both at low , so at high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltenes, and other low molecular weight molecules called maltens. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, warned an expert in chemical engineering.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers is an asphalt liner, formed by small stones embedded in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the liner is filled with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to be well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, according to the chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer, called the mantle, was placed on the asphalt insert, formed by fine stones, ie sand also embedded in the asphalt.
Due to the fact that this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a greater mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Due to the fact that it will be exposed to a large load as part of the paving, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
As soon as the terrain is moist, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult for it to get out, this causes all layers of paving to soften and thus create potholes.
He explained that during the formation of potholes, the film of the casing is destroyed first, and only then is the asphalt liner damaged. However, the damage does not occur at the same time, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of paving must match the load on vehicles and ensure that this load is not exceeded. This is the only way we can prevent frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that we still have a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt and research is just beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
