Such was the work of the resident of Cali, who identified the corpse of Alfons Can
A fingerprint expert from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of &quot;Alfonso Cana&quot;.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4 last year, a fingerprint expert from the CTI in Cali went down in history as a man who confirmed the identity of Farc&#39;s top leader: &quot;Alfonso Cana,&quot; by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working for CTI this week, it was Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejad who has been working in forensic research for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked at the town hall in Chocó, where he often had to wade through the forest for more than five days to get to a place where there were corpses that had to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital Valle and, after completing the relevant courses, began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of skin friction, ie the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against Alfonso Can, Eliazar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night, he set out for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he would have to identify two corpses, and he suspected that one of them was the man who ran the oldest guerrilla in the world. Therefore, they asked him to take a card with fingerprints of Guillermo Leon Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site of the corpse, he did not recognize him because of his physical appearance. He looked completely different than in the media.
He had no beard, dressed as a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But prints don&#39;t lie.
Along with the galton&#39;s magnifying glass, ink, and transporter and light, Eliazar began comparing the corpse&#39;s dactyl records with the card readings.
His eye did not disappoint: it was &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
That same night, a man from Puerto Tejado was instructed to confirm to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he was really the supreme commander of Farc.
Searching for tracks
For the dactyloscope from Sijín de Cali, the recognition given to Eliazaro González by President Juan Manuel Santos at a press conference of the operational service against &quot;Cana&quot; is very important.
A lot of people don&#39;t know our job.
Fingerprinting is an exact science, without the possibility of error, that can play a key role in crime decisions.
In addition to identifying corpses, these people assist in the research of crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When they catch them, a lot of delinquents present fake documents or have no papers at all.
We take their fingerprints and look them in the database.
The investigator said that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the house wall in the house, because at this point the thief was leaning to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
