This is one of the conclusions of an extensive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which included six experts working in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The commission recommends that the government change criminal law to allow for assisted suicide and euthanasia if this choice appears necessary for a patient considered competent to make such a decision.
At the beginning, experts cite a recent survey by the independent agency Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
Although Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that &quot;the medicalization of death in Canada has given rise to a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death.&quot;
Medicalization yes or no, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts with a mandate from the Royal Canadian Society tell us.
And despite the desire to die at home, which most Canadians have, 68.6% of them die in hospital.
This average is valid for the whole of Canada, while in the province of Quebec, this number is the highest with 86% of people who died in hospital.
On the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change the criminal law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
According to experts, who have also inspected all countries where these approaches are legalized or not considered a criminal case, there is no evidence that this criminalization causes any abuse in application, ie in the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide against indecent or dissenting persons.
On the contrary, Mr Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, confirmed yesterday at a teleconference more than the numerous cases of these outbursts in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
&quot;Euthanasia is also being carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.&quot;
&quot;Assisted suicide is also committed in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,&quot; explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians are in favor of euthanasia
Recall that, according to a survey conducted by the Angus Reid Forum in 2010, 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia because they believe it will allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean sending a message that the lives of the elderly or handicapped are of less value.
Regarding those who practice assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
The situation is less clear when it comes to maintaining or interrupting patient care, say the report&#39;s authors.
They also suggest in their list of recommendations that it be stated in criminal law that withdrawal from treatment for which there is a legally confirmed refusal is not a criminal offense.
The Commission of Experts also requires that medical practitioners be trained to respect end-of-life refusals without fear of prosecution.
On palliative care, the commission urges governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, including in cancer cases.
Finally, in the case of palliative or final sedation, already widely used in Canadian medical facilities, the Commission calls for it to be considered euthanasia when it is no longer used to reduce physical pain and to be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations of other experts
Some medical law experts have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of a report by experts from the Royal Society of Canada.
Mr. Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in medical law, described the position of experts-signatories to the report as &quot;extreme&quot;, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to patients in the final stages.
&quot;This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 could ask to help them commit suicide,&quot; said Pierre Deschamps, who studied the summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also emphasizes that it seems as if the authors of the report put the autonomy of the person above all the other values that make up the social fabric of society.
Because &quot;in society, he says, there are warning signs and restrictions.&quot;
Medical law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed &quot;strong objections to the conclusions of the report, which she described as a&quot; manifesto for euthanasia. &quot;
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Canadian Society, is particularly skeptical about the report&#39;s data on the absence of wrongdoing in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, ie the Netherlands and the US state of Oregon.
