the inclusion of the golden rule on a balanced budget in the constitution
The government of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include the &quot;golden rule&quot; of fiscal policy in the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade of Austria&#39;s rating agencies (AAA).
It was Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced the decision at the end of a ministerial meeting in a situation where Austria&#39;s public debt, at 74.6%, was well above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty but much lower than that of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
&quot;If Austria&#39;s solvency were reduced by just a single degree from AAA to AA +, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year,&quot; argued the vice-chancellor and foreign minister, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria follows a request from the eurozone summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the heads of state and government urged that by the end of 2012 a reduction in the public deficit and the achievement of a balance of public accounts be enshrined in a constitution or law of the same value.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is close to the &quot;German model&quot;, Germany was the first European country to adopt such a &quot;rule&quot;.
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 onwards, the federal state&#39;s public structural deficit will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the Länder as well as municipalities they will have to show a balanced budget.
The aim is to bring the public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
