Energy policy:
facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balance sheets or under emotion, then it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is natural for the election meeting to be an opportunity to think about such contributions and the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand between 2050, unless we want to deprive a large part of the world&#39;s population of important parts of life.
At the same time, the shortage of fossil resources will need to be addressed in order to continue to generate electricity, without forgetting the need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The accident in Fukushima does not affect any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
However, this is not the case in Belgium, which makes its decision subject to the need to find another source capable of replacing itself, or Switzerland, which considers it appropriate to build only the latest generation power plants.
By contrast, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to cite at least some countries, are continuing their determination with their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its fleet by one unit by resuming construction of a power plant suspended after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model based on renewable energies is ever presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of power plants for natural gas and coal.
We will feel all these unpleasant effects within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
