Nord Stream, a new Russian gas port of entry into Europe
The long-distance Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has become operational.
It has to supply gas equivalent to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including 4 heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned the control wheel together to control the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the federal state of Mecklemberg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will make it possible to supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, a quantity equal to all French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany without being routed through the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, the two countries are losing some of their power: the possibility of pushing Russia on threats to foreclose Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw put it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the &quot;new German-Soviet pact&quot;, referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying that this is a politically sensitive subject.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe gained greater security of its purchases in it.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe&#39;s energy, as the project has created cracks between Europeans from the East and the West.
Barely 5 years ago, Russia succeeded in asserting its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich, gas-consuming Western nations whose deposits were coming to an end.
&quot;This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,&quot; François Fillon confirmed at the grand opening of the pipeline, demonstrating the point at which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It rests on the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
&quot;For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,&quot; said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect fauna and flora also needed to be stepped up.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted anywhere along its length by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company settling permanently off their coast.
&quot;In the event of a fault, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,&quot; says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welds were designed so that the leak occurs once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline from the outside is checked by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the finish line after a full three days of travel at a speed of 3 m / s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains the leader, holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company all its gas transmission capacity for five years under a renewable contract.
&quot;Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,&quot; says Jens Müller.
Financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be recouped, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore with pine forests.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
