Why is the share of unemployed handicapped workers so high?
Around 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Handicapped opens today.
Despite the voluntaristic public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled people is twice as high as the average, ie 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
&quot;No, underlines Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, which organizes a Week for the Employment of the Handicapped.&quot;
&quot;The progress made in 15 years is remarkable.&quot;
&quot;At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher.&quot;
&quot;However, much remains to be done.&quot;
It must be said that numerous obstacles remain for unemployed disabled people before they start work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma and only 10,000 are 2.3 million university students.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% of the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are criteria that make returning to work particularly difficult and which are the &quot;core of the problem&quot;, according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, which was set up in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unspoken, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slow.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the interviewed managers had a &quot;low level of knowledge about disabled people&quot; with an &quot;exaggerated idea of wheelchair users and mental or mental deficiencies&quot;.
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures, which come from 2008, indicate a situation of 2.6%.
&quot;We are now around 3%,&quot; said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which is responsible for collecting fees from companies that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of &quot;fined&quot; companies, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 offending companies to 46,000 (from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put strong pressure on businesses,&quot; explains Pierre Blanc.
&quot;But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large companies.&quot;
According to the Ministry of Labor, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees employ handicapped workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
